const questions = [
  {
    id: 1,
    type: "Strengthen",
    stimulus: `A city council recently installed speed bumps on Maple Street to reduce traffic accidents. In the six months following installation, the number of reported accidents on Maple Street decreased by 40 percent. The council concluded that speed bumps are an effective method for reducing traffic accidents in residential areas.`,
    stem: "Which one of the following, if true, most strengthens the city council's conclusion?",
    choices: [
      { letter: "A", text: "Several other streets in the city without speed bumps saw no change in accident rates during the same period." },
      { letter: "B", text: "The speed bumps on Maple Street cost significantly less to install than traffic signals would have." },
      { letter: "C", text: "Most of the accidents on Maple Street prior to the installation involved vehicles traveling above the speed limit." },
      { letter: "D", text: "Residents of Maple Street had petitioned the council for traffic safety measures for over two years." },
      { letter: "E", text: "The city also installed new streetlights on Maple Street at the same time as the speed bumps." },
    ],
    correct: "A",
    explanation: "Choice A strengthens the argument by ruling out the possibility that the decrease was part of a city-wide trend unrelated to the speed bumps. If streets without speed bumps saw no improvement, the bumps are more likely the cause. Choice E actually weakens the argument by introducing an alternative explanation. Choice C is tempting but addresses why accidents happened, not whether speed bumps caused the reduction.",
  },
  {
    id: 2,
    type: "Weaken",
    stimulus: `A pharmaceutical company argues that its new allergy medication is superior to existing treatments because in clinical trials, 85 percent of participants reported symptom relief within one hour of taking the medication. No existing allergy medication has achieved a relief rate higher than 70 percent in comparable trials.`,
    stem: "Which one of the following, if true, most seriously weakens the pharmaceutical company's argument?",
    choices: [
      { letter: "A", text: "The clinical trial participants were selected from a group of individuals with only mild allergy symptoms." },
      { letter: "B", text: "Some participants in the trial experienced minor side effects such as drowsiness." },
      { letter: "C", text: "The company has previously developed other successful allergy medications." },
      { letter: "D", text: "The trial measured symptom relief based on participant self-reporting rather than clinical observation." },
      { letter: "E", text: "Allergy medications generally take between 30 minutes and two hours to produce noticeable effects." },
    ],
    correct: "A",
    explanation: "Choice A undermines the comparison. If the trial only included people with mild symptoms, the 85% relief rate may not reflect the medication's effectiveness against the full range of allergy severity that existing medications were tested on. The comparison is therefore unfair. Choice D raises a methodological concern but applies equally to any trial using self-reporting, so it doesn't specifically weaken this comparison.",
  },
  {
    id: 3,
    type: "Flaw",
    stimulus: `Every student in Professor Ward's advanced seminar received a grade of A. Kira is a student at the university where Professor Ward teaches. Therefore, Kira received a grade of A in Professor Ward's seminar.`,
    stem: "The reasoning in the argument is flawed because the argument",
    choices: [
      { letter: "A", text: "assumes that what is true of a group must be true of every institution associated with that group" },
      { letter: "B", text: "takes for granted that Kira is enrolled in Professor Ward's seminar" },
      { letter: "C", text: "confuses a necessary condition with a sufficient condition" },
      { letter: "D", text: "draws a conclusion about a specific case based on evidence that is purely statistical" },
      { letter: "E", text: "fails to consider that Professor Ward may teach courses other than the advanced seminar" },
    ],
    correct: "B",
    explanation: "The argument's central flaw is an unwarranted assumption: it assumes Kira is in the seminar simply because she attends the same university. Being a student at the university does not mean she is enrolled in that particular course. This is a classic scope error — the premise about seminar students is applied to someone who may not be in the seminar at all.",
  },
  {
    id: 4,
    type: "Must Be True",
    stimulus: `All of the paintings displayed in the east wing of the gallery were completed before 1900. Some of the paintings displayed in the east wing are by French artists. No painting by a French artist in the gallery's collection was completed before 1850.`,
    stem: "If the statements above are true, which one of the following must also be true?",
    choices: [
      { letter: "A", text: "All paintings by French artists in the gallery were completed between 1850 and 1900." },
      { letter: "B", text: "Some paintings displayed in the east wing were completed between 1850 and 1900." },
      { letter: "C", text: "No painting completed after 1900 is displayed in the east wing." },
      { letter: "D", text: "Most paintings in the gallery's collection were completed before 1900." },
      { letter: "E", text: "Some French paintings in the gallery were not completed before 1850." },
    ],
    correct: "B",
    explanation: "From the premises: east wing paintings are all pre-1900; some east wing paintings are by French artists; no French painting in the collection is pre-1850. So the French paintings in the east wing must be from 1850–1899. Therefore, some east wing paintings were completed between 1850 and 1900. Choice A goes too far — it covers all French paintings in the gallery, not just those in the east wing. Choice C restates the first premise but is already given, while B derives new information from combining all three premises.",
  },
  {
    id: 5,
    type: "Parallel Reasoning",
    stimulus: `Anyone who regularly practices an instrument will improve their technique. Dana does not regularly practice any instrument. Therefore, Dana will not improve her technique.`,
    stem: "Which one of the following arguments exhibits reasoning most similar to the flawed reasoning in the argument above?",
    choices: [
      { letter: "A", text: "All employees who complete the training program receive a certification. Raj did not complete the training program. Therefore, Raj will not receive a certification." },
      { letter: "B", text: "Every car in the lot has been inspected. This vehicle has been inspected. Therefore, this vehicle is in the lot." },
      { letter: "C", text: "Students who study regularly tend to perform well. Maria studies regularly. Therefore, Maria will perform well." },
      { letter: "D", text: "All members of the committee voted in favour of the proposal. Sami is not a member of the committee. Therefore, Sami did not vote in favour of the proposal." },
      { letter: "E", text: "Anyone who finishes the race will receive a medal. Tomás finished the race. Therefore, Tomás will receive a medal." },
    ],
    correct: "D",
    explanation: "The original argument commits the fallacy of denying the antecedent: 'If practice → improve. No practice. Therefore no improvement.' This is flawed because improvement could come from other sources. Choice D mirrors this exactly: 'If committee member → voted yes. Not a member. Therefore didn't vote yes.' Sami could have voted yes as a non-member observer. Choice A has the same structure and is tempting, but certification programs typically require completion — making it more plausible. Choice D better parallels the flaw because voting is clearly not restricted to committee members.",
  },
  {
    id: 6,
    type: "Assumption",
    stimulus: `A restaurant critic argues that Chez Laurent must be the best restaurant in the city because it has received more five-star reviews from diners than any other restaurant in the city over the past year.`,
    stem: "The argument relies on which one of the following assumptions?",
    choices: [
      { letter: "A", text: "Chez Laurent has been open for at least one year." },
      { letter: "B", text: "The number of five-star reviews a restaurant receives is a reliable indicator of the restaurant's quality." },
      { letter: "C", text: "No restaurant outside the city has received more five-star reviews than Chez Laurent." },
      { letter: "D", text: "The restaurant critic has personally dined at Chez Laurent." },
      { letter: "E", text: "Five-star reviews are more difficult to earn than four-star reviews." },
    ],
    correct: "B",
    explanation: "The argument moves from 'most five-star reviews' to 'best restaurant.' This leap requires assuming that review quantity reflects quality. Without this bridge, the conclusion doesn't follow — a restaurant could have more reviews simply because it has more customers, runs promotions for reviews, or has been open longer. This is a necessary assumption: deny it, and the argument collapses.",
  },
  {
    id: 7,
    type: "Resolve the Paradox",
    stimulus: `A wildlife biologist observed that in a particular forest, the population of owls increased by 25 percent over five years. During the same period, the population of mice — the owls' primary food source in that forest — also increased by a comparable percentage.`,
    stem: "Which one of the following, if true, most helps to explain the surprising fact that the mouse population increased despite the growth in the owl population?",
    choices: [
      { letter: "A", text: "Owls also prey on small birds and insects in addition to mice." },
      { letter: "B", text: "A logging operation near the forest created new open ground that greatly expanded the mice's habitat and food supply." },
      { letter: "C", text: "The owl population in a neighbouring forest remained stable during the same period." },
      { letter: "D", text: "Mice reproduce at a faster rate than most other small mammals." },
      { letter: "E", text: "Some of the owls in the forest migrated from other regions." },
    ],
    correct: "B",
    explanation: "The paradox is: more predators (owls) should mean fewer prey (mice), yet mice also increased. Choice B resolves this by introducing a factor — expanded habitat from logging — that would boost the mouse population enough to outpace increased predation. Choice D addresses reproduction rates generally but doesn't explain why the increase happened during this specific period.",
  },
  {
    id: 8,
    type: "Method of Reasoning",
    stimulus: `Yara: The proposed bike lane on King Street will reduce car traffic congestion. When bike lanes were added on Queen Street last year, car commute times on that street dropped by 15 percent within six months.

    Marcus: But King Street is a major commercial corridor with heavy delivery truck traffic, unlike Queen Street, which is primarily residential. The situations are not comparable.`,
    stem: "Marcus responds to Yara's argument by",
    choices: [
      { letter: "A", text: "providing evidence that directly contradicts Yara's statistical claim" },
      { letter: "B", text: "questioning the relevance of Yara's evidence by identifying a significant difference between the two cases" },
      { letter: "C", text: "arguing that bike lanes generally do not reduce congestion" },
      { letter: "D", text: "suggesting that Yara's conclusion is based on too small a sample size" },
      { letter: "E", text: "introducing an alternative proposal for reducing congestion on King Street" },
    ],
    correct: "B",
    explanation: "Marcus doesn't dispute the Queen Street data itself. Instead, he argues that King Street is fundamentally different (commercial vs. residential, truck traffic vs. none), making Yara's analogy unreliable. This is a classic method of reasoning answer: attacking the analogy by highlighting a relevant disanalogy between the two cases.",
  },
  {
    id: 9,
    type: "Principle",
    stimulus: `A school board decided not to renew the contract of a teacher who had received satisfactory performance reviews for ten consecutive years. The board cited budget constraints as the sole reason. Several parents objected, arguing that the decision was unfair.`,
    stem: "Which one of the following principles, if valid, most supports the parents' objection?",
    choices: [
      { letter: "A", text: "Budget constraints should never be a factor in employment decisions." },
      { letter: "B", text: "An employee with a consistently satisfactory record should not be terminated unless there is a performance-based reason." },
      { letter: "C", text: "School boards should always defer to the preferences of parents when making staffing decisions." },
      { letter: "D", text: "Teachers with more than five years of experience should automatically receive tenure." },
      { letter: "E", text: "Employees should be terminated only when their positions are being permanently eliminated." },
    ],
    correct: "B",
    explanation: "The parents believe the decision is unfair because the teacher performed well. Choice B captures this principle: consistently good performance should protect against non-performance-based termination. Choice A is too extreme (budget constraints are sometimes legitimate). Choice E is too narrow and introduces a condition not at issue.",
  },
  {
    id: 10,
    type: "Strengthen",
    stimulus: `Researchers found that employees who work from home at least three days per week report higher job satisfaction than those who work exclusively in the office. The researchers concluded that remote work arrangements cause increased job satisfaction.`,
    stem: "Which one of the following, if true, most strengthens the researchers' conclusion?",
    choices: [
      { letter: "A", text: "Employees who work from home tend to have longer tenures at their companies." },
      { letter: "B", text: "The study controlled for differences in job type, salary, and seniority between the two groups." },
      { letter: "C", text: "Many companies have expanded their remote work policies in recent years." },
      { letter: "D", text: "Employees who work from home save money on commuting and meals." },
      { letter: "E", text: "Job satisfaction surveys are widely regarded as reliable measures of employee sentiment." },
    ],
    correct: "B",
    explanation: "The argument makes a causal claim (remote work causes higher satisfaction), but the evidence is correlational. Choice B strengthens the causal claim by ruling out confounding variables — if the groups were comparable in job type, salary, and seniority, the remaining difference (remote vs. office) is more likely the cause. Choice D provides a possible mechanism but doesn't rule out alternative explanations for the correlation.",
  },
  {
    id: 11,
    type: "Weaken",
    stimulus: `A fitness company claims that its new high-intensity workout program is the most effective way to build muscle. The company points to a study in which participants who followed the program gained an average of three kilograms of muscle over eight weeks, more than participants in any other study the company reviewed.`,
    stem: "Which one of the following, if true, most seriously weakens the fitness company's claim?",
    choices: [
      { letter: "A", text: "The participants in the company's study were also placed on a high-protein diet designed to maximize muscle growth." },
      { letter: "B", text: "High-intensity workout programs carry a greater risk of injury than moderate-intensity programs." },
      { letter: "C", text: "The company sells supplements that it recommends pairing with the workout program." },
      { letter: "D", text: "Some participants in the study had previous experience with strength training." },
      { letter: "E", text: "The study was conducted over a relatively short period of eight weeks." },
    ],
    correct: "A",
    explanation: "If participants were also on a specially designed high-protein diet, the muscle gains may be attributable to the diet rather than (or in addition to) the workout program alone. This introduces a confounding variable that undermines the claim that the program itself is what produced superior results. The other studies reviewed may not have included such dietary controls.",
  },
  {
    id: 12,
    type: "Flaw",
    stimulus: `A newspaper editorial argued: "The proposed waterfront development will be good for the local economy. A survey of 200 business owners in the waterfront district found that 80 percent support the development. Clearly, the community at large favours this project."`,
    stem: "The reasoning in the editorial is most vulnerable to criticism on the grounds that it",
    choices: [
      { letter: "A", text: "fails to consider whether the development might have negative environmental consequences" },
      { letter: "B", text: "treats the opinions of a group that has a direct financial interest in the outcome as representative of the broader community" },
      { letter: "C", text: "does not specify the exact number of business owners who were surveyed" },
      { letter: "D", text: "assumes that economic benefits are the only relevant consideration in evaluating the development" },
      { letter: "E", text: "relies on a survey rather than a binding vote to gauge community support" },
    ],
    correct: "B",
    explanation: "The editorial generalizes from waterfront business owners to the entire community. Business owners in the affected district have a direct financial stake in the development and are not representative of the broader public. This is a biased sample flaw. Choice C is wrong because the editorial does specify 200. Choice A and D raise different issues but don't address the core reasoning error.",
  },
  {
    id: 13,
    type: "Must Be True",
    stimulus: `In a technology company, all senior engineers have completed the advanced certification program. Some senior engineers have also completed the leadership training course. No employee who has completed the leadership training course has fewer than five years of experience at the company.`,
    stem: "If the statements above are true, which one of the following must also be true?",
    choices: [
      { letter: "A", text: "All employees with more than five years of experience have completed the leadership training course." },
      { letter: "B", text: "Some employees who have completed the advanced certification program have at least five years of experience." },
      { letter: "C", text: "No senior engineer has fewer than five years of experience at the company." },
      { letter: "D", text: "All employees who have completed both programs are senior engineers." },
      { letter: "E", text: "Some employees with fewer than five years of experience have completed the advanced certification program." },
    ],
    correct: "B",
    explanation: "Some senior engineers completed leadership training. All who completed leadership training have 5+ years of experience. So those senior engineers have 5+ years. All senior engineers completed advanced certification. Therefore, some people who completed advanced certification (namely those senior engineers) have 5+ years of experience. Choice C goes too far — only senior engineers who did leadership training necessarily have 5+ years; other senior engineers might not.",
  },
  {
    id: 14,
    type: "Assumption",
    stimulus: `A city planner argues that converting the unused railway corridor into a public park will reduce crime in the surrounding neighbourhood. She notes that neighbourhoods with well-maintained public green spaces tend to have lower crime rates than those without such spaces.`,
    stem: "The city planner's argument requires the assumption that",
    choices: [
      { letter: "A", text: "the railway corridor is large enough to be converted into a meaningful green space" },
      { letter: "B", text: "the presence of well-maintained green spaces contributes to lower crime rates rather than merely being correlated with other factors that reduce crime" },
      { letter: "C", text: "no other measures are being considered to reduce crime in the neighbourhood" },
      { letter: "D", text: "the park will attract visitors from outside the neighbourhood" },
      { letter: "E", text: "the railway corridor is currently a site where crimes are frequently committed" },
    ],
    correct: "B",
    explanation: "The planner moves from a correlation (green spaces and lower crime tend to appear together) to a causal prediction (adding green space will reduce crime). This requires assuming the relationship is causal, not merely that wealthier or better-resourced neighbourhoods happen to have both parks and lower crime. Without this assumption, building the park might not affect crime at all.",
  },
  {
    id: 15,
    type: "Resolve the Paradox",
    stimulus: `A bookstore that switched from printed receipts to email receipts expected to reduce its operating costs. However, in the year after the switch, the bookstore's total operating costs increased by four percent.`,
    stem: "Which one of the following, if true, most helps to resolve the apparent discrepancy described above?",
    choices: [
      { letter: "A", text: "Many customers preferred printed receipts and complained about the change." },
      { letter: "B", text: "The bookstore's rent increased significantly during the same year due to a new lease agreement." },
      { letter: "C", text: "Email receipts require a software subscription that costs approximately the same as the paper and ink previously used." },
      { letter: "D", text: "Other bookstores in the area continued to offer printed receipts." },
      { letter: "E", text: "The bookstore hired additional staff during the same period to handle increased foot traffic." },
    ],
    correct: "B",
    explanation: "The paradox is: a cost-saving measure was implemented, yet costs rose. Choice B resolves this by identifying an independent cost increase (rent) that outweighed the savings from switching to email receipts. The receipt change may well have saved money, but a larger expense increase elsewhere drove total costs up. Choice C would explain why there were no savings, but not why costs increased by 4%.",
  },
];
